<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Chromaticity" class="currentChild" href="Chromaticity">Chromaticity</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
The color quality of a visual impulse (i.e., light) described only in terms of its dominant <a title="Hue" href="Hue">hue</a> (or wavelength) and its <a title="Saturation" href="Saturation">saturation</a>, without needing to take into account the <a title="Value" href="Value">value</a>—or <a title="Brightness" href="Brightness">brightness</a>—of the color. When describing light, chromaticity refers to the proportions of two of the three <a title="Primary Colors" href="Primary_Colors">primary colors</a> that constitute a particular color. See <a title="CIE Color Space" href="CIE_Color_Space">CIE Color Space</a>. 
</p>
